Compassion and tact are free. Offer up your ear to listen to these humans’ concerns for their homeland(s), families, and friends. Listen. I will say that again, Listen. They are worried. They are scared. Show them love, support, and confirm their feelings are valid. 💖

My tire was flat again this morning. 🤦🏼‍♀️ I said a prayer as I filled it with air, again, at the Sheetz prior to our hour long drive home on the highway that it would stay inflated to make it home, and it did. 🙌🏻 The tire shop found a 1in nail as the culprit and sealed the hole.

In fact, on the drive home he couldn’t stop talking about Darby Allin and Wardlow, and my younger nephew couldn’t stop gushing over seeing Jungle Boy wrestle. I love these boys and I’m glad, even despite our little misadventures, they had a blast and enjoyed their Christmas gift.

I love being an aunt to these sweet boys and, taking the tough times like late last night and this morning when I couldn’t help make him feel better, comes with being their aunt. When I asked him if he enjoyed the event, despite the way things ended, he said an enthusiastic, YES!

Only to find one of my tires was nearly flat. 🤦🏼‍♀️ I really wanted to get my nephew to bed ASAP because I know what he needed the most then was some rest, but alas a pit stop by Sheetz had to happen first. After that, he got a quick bath, then we all were in bed.

Nothing like having to be the person in the bathroom getting the sick off my nephew’s T-shirt, shoe, hands, and face. RIP to the Santa hat. 🪦That was not coming home. 😬 I made sure he was okay and then all 3 of us traipsed back to the car…

The poor fella, we feel after talking later, just got overstimulated. It was a late night, he ate a lot of food, it got hot, and wrestling events can be pretty chaotic in general with all the lights and sounds. Well, all of that combined, he got sick.

Last night was a great experience for me and my nephews up until the very last match of the night…of the recording for Rampage. One of my nephews has a lot of health issues, and I did my best to try to prevent what happened, but sometimes it’s unpredictable.
My nephew last night was like, “that guy is wearing pajamas”. 🤣 I was like, “No. Please put some respect on the festive romper or two piece set, sir”. https://t.co/Q2ZtTvBCRV

While I was never diagnosed diabetic, I was at one point in my life pre-diabetic. I spent a year in a diabetes program, monitoring my meals I ate, my exercise routines, etc. I made A LOT of sacrifices to get my A1C back in the normal range to reverse my diagnosis.

Just here to randomly tweet out it’s insensitive af to tell someone to change their diet and exercise habits and they’ll be cured of their type 2 diabetes. It’s not that simple.
